<font face="Comic Sans MS" size="2">
<table border="0" cellspacing="10">
<font size="5">bell</font><br>
<br>
format:&nbsp&nbsp &nbsp&nbsp &nbsp&nbsp  <a href="http://ytin.sourceforge.net/cgi-bin/help.pl/ytin?c-bell">#bell</a> [level=5]<br>
							<a href="http://ytin.sourceforge.net/cgi-bin/help.pl/ytin?c-bell">#bell</a> threshold [threshold]<br>
<br>
sends a beep to your terminal when level>=threshold.<br>
default level and threshold are all 5.<br>
<br>
&nbsp&nbsp &nbsp&nbsp &nbsp&nbsp &nbsp&nbsp &nbsp&nbsp &nbsp&nbsp &nbsp&nbsp <a href="http://ytin.sourceforge.net/cgi-bin/help.pl/ytin?c-bell">#bell</a> option [option] [frequency] [duration]<br>
This option is for windows only: 0: soundcard, 1: speaker.<br>
For speaker, user can specify the frequency (all) and duration (not for 95/98/Me) of the beep.<br>
<br>
example:<br>
<a href="http://ytin.sourceforge.net/cgi-bin/help.pl/ytin?c-action">#action</a> {tells you} {<a href="http://ytin.sourceforge.net/cgi-bin/help.pl/ytin?c-bell">#bell</a>}<br>
<a href="http://ytin.sourceforge.net/cgi-bin/help.pl/ytin?c-action">#action</a> {you are in danger!!!} {<a href="http://ytin.sourceforge.net/cgi-bin/help.pl/ytin?c-bell">#bell</a> 9}<br>
In normal case, both action will chime you.<br>
<br>
Now you only want the 2nd case to send u a beep:<br>
<a href="http://ytin.sourceforge.net/cgi-bin/help.pl/ytin?c-bell">#bell</a> threshold 6<br>
Since <a href="http://ytin.sourceforge.net/cgi-bin/help.pl/ytin?c-bell">#bell</a> == <a href="http://ytin.sourceforge.net/cgi-bin/help.pl/ytin?c-bell">#bell</a> 5 is below the threshold 6, only<br>
the second action will send a real beep.<br>
<br>
</table>
